  "chunk_index": 27,
  "summary": "Spence and Poirot discuss the murder of Mrs. Upward, noting that the killer was likely someone she knew. Evidence at the scene included two coffee cups; while the guest's fingerprints were wiped away, lipstick traces remained on a rim. Spence notes that Mrs. Upward had recognized a photo of Lily Gambol, linking the crime to the McQuitty murder case. It is believed Mrs. Upward was playing detective and called a guest to her home at Golden Chain Manor while her son, Robin, and Mrs. Oliver were at the theater. The maid, Frieda, was in her room and did not witness the event.\n\nDierdre Henderson arrives to provide a statement. She claims Mrs. Upward called her to invite her for coffee between 8:30 and 9:00 PM. However, when Dierdre arrived, the house was dark and no one answered. She assumed Mrs. Upward had gone to the theater and left to go for a walk. Spence observes that Dierdre does not wear lipstick or perfume, which contrasts with the expensive perfume scent reported by Mrs. Oliver and Robin Upward at the scene. \n\nSpence considers whether Dierdre could be Lily Garfield, though he notes their backgrounds differ. He also contemplates Eve Carrington as a suspect, noting she can afford expensive perfume. Finally, Spence confirms that a sugar hammer is the murder weapon, matching the wounds from the McQuitty case and containing traces of human blood.",
